    walk: `Look at this verse. Do you remember the first time you read it? Day 1 — the loop screaming, your hands maybe shaking, not even sure God was listening. I handed it to you and called it God's phone number, and the only job you had was two words: God, help.

Thirty days later, here it is again. Same verse. Different person reading it.

This is the last page where it's just you and me, so let me say what a brother says at the door. You're not finished — you're equipped. We never promised cured; we promised the truth, and the truth is the fight goes on. The devil will keep coming. He'll bring the old faces back around. He'll wait out your strong seasons and probe your tired ones. He'll whisper, somewhere down the road, that you should open the doors God closed. You know all this now — not because I scared you with it, but because you've been briefed, armored, drilled, and carried. There will be battles. Maybe not every hour. Not every day. Maybe not even every month. But they will come — and you know exactly what to do.

Because here's everything this book taught you, and it fits in one line: you just dial His number.

That's it. That was always it. Thirty days, four weeks, twenty-nine chapters — and the whole armory comes down to this: the God who answered you on the floor answers. Every time. The hundredth call like the first. Before you call, He's already answering — you lived that before you ever read it. The pillar goes ahead of you, cloud by day, fire by night, and the line to Him is never busy and never closed. You will never face one single hour — not the 2 AM ones, not the doorbell ones, not the ordinary Tuesday ambush — where Jeremiah 33:3 has stopped being true.

And don't skip the last half of the verse — it's been waiting thirty days for you to be ready for it: "...and shew thee great and mighty things, which thou knowest not." The number isn't just for emergencies, beloved. The same line that carried you through withdrawal is the line God uses to show you what He's building next — things you don't even know about yet. A life you can't picture from here. People you'll pull out of the same hell, with this same testimony. Maybe somebody, someday, sitting across from you on their Day 1, while you hand them God's phone number with steady hands. The mess became a message. Now the message goes walking.

So here's the send-off, and then I'll let you go. The first day or two of the rest of your life won't be the hardest — you already survived the hardest. There will be aching days and there will be glory days, and the same God is in both. Walk connected. Suit up daily. Keep your cord close. Set your stones. And every single time — every flash of the old fire, every knock, every wave —

you know the number. Dial it.

He answers. He always has. I'm living proof — and now, so are you.

Go in peace, brother. Go in peace, sister. The LORD goes before you.`,
    prayer: `Father — thirty days ago I called You from the floor and You answered a person who barely believed You were there. Now I'm standing. Not cured — carried. Not finished — equipped. So I'm sealing Your number in my heart where nothing can take it: Jeremiah 33:3. For every battle still coming, for every great and mighty thing You haven't shown me yet — I will call, and You will answer. All the way home, Lord. In Jesus' name — Amen.`,
